{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dce95f8b-42a9-440d-a9a9-15e553243a51","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest for .NET-specific CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper OS-level detail)\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView uses ETW and captures both managed and native stacks — better if you suspect the issue is outside your .NET code (GC, JIT, kernel).\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for simplicity. Escalate to PerfView if you need OS/native context.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a03e6b39-ef68-4cad-aa41-6ec5be1319f0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a general knowledge question about performance diagnostics - no code changes or file operations needed.","outputTokens":314,"requestId":"5036:B7F6F:20F636:28F0E4:69F5518D"},"id":"11b16d43-14d2-4cc5-8d1d-db2713ae8350","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:21:25.451Z","parentId":"2ba4627a-e964-45db-94c5-e9bf66af8202"}
